Text.Value: Apology accepted.
If I can help, I will.
Weren't your people exiled from Baldur's Gate?
We'll be heading for Baldur's Gate soon. If fate wills it, I'll see you there.
Last I saw you, you were disappearing on a boat down the river.
*Sigh.* Foolish and ignorant, like the rest. But you'll change your mind once you see what's become of Baldur's Gate, I have no doubt.
I wasn't sure you would - I appreciate it.
In a sense - yes. But that's because I didn't know what you were capable of.
Leave.
Gently pierce the veil of his mind, probing for his true intentions.
Not my finest exit. I hid out on the river until the sky lit up. Couldn't believe my eyes - especially when I realised you were behind it.
Heh. That's I like to hear. You're worth ten of my crew.
And that's precisely why I want you by my side in Baldur's Gate.

EditorData.NodeContext: to wulbren, this is a huge deal to offer the player

Text.Value: Siding with a murderous lunatic is more than 'foolish'.
But our forebears were foolish - complicit with Sarevok's madness over a century past, and so we were banished. Still are to this day.
Bring every scrap of courage you have to Baldur's Gate - you'll need it for what's to come.
Good luck with that.
*You see a column of fire that dominates the sky in a blazing inferno - nothing more.*
I've filled appeals - pleaded with the High Artificer himself. They've refused us time and again. Now, however, I will make them listen.
*You recall stories of the Ironhand Gnomes - a talented group of inventors who were banished from Baldur's Gate.*
I see Gondian propaganda is alive and well. We match the High House of Wonders in design. Innovation. Brilliance.
But I stand by what I said before - you and I were meant to meet. And together, we'll save Baldur's Gate from itself.
That's what I like to hear. Find me in the city - and together, we can save Baldur's Gate from itself.
Wait until you reach the city. Once you see what it's become, you'll know the Ironhand Gnomes are needed.
Inventors? Traitors, more like. Every gnome in Baldur's Gate suffered for your treachery.
And I'm not a man easily impressed.
I apologise - for not seeing your true worth. And for being, quite frankly, rude in Last Light.
I can be rude myself sometimes.
Find me in the city - once you see what it's become, you'll know that I and I alone can stop it.
You agree with such machinations? Duly noted.
If you want my help, I'm going to need more to go on.
Gracious as well as impressive - a fine combination.
I am Wulbren Bongle, leader of the Ironhand Gnomes. No doubt you've heard of us?
Problem is, Baldur's Gate is sick. Once the pinnacle of greatness, it's eating itself alive to save itself from starving.

EditorData.NodeContext: slight hint of gravity here - player should wonder what he's planning

Text.Value: The Ironhand Gnomes are going to save the city - and you can be part of it.

EditorData.NodeContext: sincere and grave - this is a huge thing for wulbren to offer

Text.Value: I saw you as a means to escape, nothing more. But when the sky lit up - when I followed it here - I knew you were behind it.
I don't know much, I'm afraid.
I believe the words you're looking for are 'thank you'.
You were being an arsehole.
For what?
I do what I can.
Pity he never succeeded.
Doing a job without information is a surefire way to get caught. Spill.
We're outnumbered, my friend - and secrecy is a slim advantage. I'll tell you more in the city.
I underestimated you. Kept who I was, and who I represent, from you - but I see now that was a mistake.
It's Barcus you should apologise to. Your reunion in Last Light was... strained.
I met some Ironhand Gnomes looking for runepowder in the Underdark - any idea why?
I'm no scholar of history - what are you talking about?
I've fought tooth and nail to restore our reputation. Particularly against Gondian detractors who live in glass houses.
It was out of pure necessity - I imagine you'd have done the same if our roles were reversed.

EditorData.NodeContext: dodging player's accusations, turning it back on them

Text.Value: Our cause is just and righteous, friend. That's all the luck we need.
To use it as all innovators do - for the good of the realm. Nothing to concern yourself with.

EditorData.NodeContext: slight smirk here at his own inside joke

Text.Value: Details. Now.
Well? Will you help me or not?
Sarevok? The Bhaalspawn?
We are inventors of the highest order, matched, perhaps, but never surpassed by the Gondians at the High House of Wonders.
Yes, our forebears were complicit with Sarevok's madness. But it was a century ago, and nothing more than foolishness.
Perhaps. But why should I be punished for a mistake I took no part in?
Is there anything I can do to help?
Yet they banished us from Baldur's Gate. And for what?
No thanks.
Hence why you're here, and they're dead.
I owe you an apology.
He was hardly a challenge.
I kill Ketheric, and suddenly we're friends, are we?
Sarevok was a madman and a murderer. He brought Baldur's Gate to the brink of destruction. And we were fool enough to work with him.
Barcus and I are another matter - I'm dealing with you right now.
Do not speak of a story you only know the half of.
Plenty. Find me in the city, and help us save Baldur's Gate from itself.
Go on. I'm sure you're dying to tell me all about the Ironhand Gnomes.
I'm listening.
Were I a Gondian, I'd keep you out of the city too.
Indeed. You're worth ten of my own crew - that is clear to see.
The plan is what it's always been - to bring the work and innovations of the Ironhand Gnomes to every corner of the realm.
Find us in Baldur's Gate. You'll see the Ironhand Gnomes in a new light - I guarantee it.
There are few as innovative as the Ironhand Gnomes. Your creations were ingenious.
The very one. It's the only mistake the Ironhand Gnomes ever made - and it cost us everything.
Tough, but fair.

EditorData.NodeContext: a slight smile - player just called him an asshole

Text.Value: You helped me escape this hellspit, then took down the heart of Moonrise - Ketheric himself. I'm impressed.

EditorData.logicalname: Never went to LL/Didn't speak in LL

Text.Value: Have you forgotten the bit where you left me behind.
I was getting to that, but all right - thank you.
Back in my cell, I didn't tell you everything - about who I was, and more importantly, who I represent.
Thank you, but there is no 'were'. We are inventors of the highest order, matched, perhaps, but never surpassed by the Gondians at the High House of Wonders.

EditorData.NodeContext: clearly carries hate towards the gondians

Synopsis: This dialogue is peak Wulbren. If he's met you in haven (after you saved him), he rolls back on how rude he was as he realises the player would be an amazing asset in the city. If this is your first time meeting him since the escape (if haven is destroyed he waits out on the river until this scene in the epilogue), he realises how good the player would be to have on his side in the city and tells him all about how wronged the ironhand gnomes were.
